**Introduction**
    The TLM, Transaction level modeling, permits SystemC processes to communicate via function calls, it is important to highlight that TLM is more about communication between the processes than algorithms they perform. In HW1, the goal was to to implement a Gaussian blur filter with SystemC modules connected with systemC FIFO channels, In this Homework, the primary goal is to use TLM-2.0 interconnect to connect the two modules, Gaussian blur and Testbench. The Testbench, software will be serve as primary initiator to initiate new transactions, the Gaussian blur module will be the final target where a fixed kernel will be placed to do the computer. Most importantly, in between the initiator and target, there is a bus, served as both initiator and target.

**Gaussian Filter Architecture**
    ![Gaussian Filter Architecture](HW2_architecture.png)
    
   as shown above, we have one primary initiator(Testbench), one Final Target(Gaussian Filter), and a Simple bus as mentioned, an initiator and a target. The testebench generates the transactions, sends them out through i_skt which is connected to the target part of the simple bus via t_skt[0]. As the role of the bus is to forward the transactions, it will do so without modifying their content; the initiator part of the bus is connect to the final target(t_skt) via i_skt[0].


**Testbench Module**
    The testbench module(software), which is initiating the transactions, first take the input image, registers its size, calculating the average weigths pixel, which is just a part of a transaction known as data, to then be sent to the bus.
   
**The Simple bus**
    The simple bus, an interconnect component will take the transaction from the initiator and passes it forward to the target(Gaussian Filter), without modifying the content, the transactions passed in our case includes Gaussian Filter inner addresses.
    
**Gaussian Filter**
    The final target which has two main methods: do_filter() and the blocking_transport(), has for role compute the convolution of the pixels sent by the testbench with the kernel, it is home to the kernel. The blocking_transport() will check whether the result is available as well as to write the result to the exact address if no error occurs.
    
    
**Result**
    The simulation time is estimated to be 2686976 ns, as compared to the one in Homework 1, the latency is higher. However, the goal was to use TLM to monitor the hardware, and for subsequent transaction, it may take less time as next time the function call will be evoked, it can simply use the address of Gaussian filter.
